    └── package.json
```

## Conventions

- **One program, many stacks.** A *stack* is an isolated instance of the infrastructure
  (`dev`, `prod`). Never branch on environment with `if` in code — put per-environment values
  in `Pulumi.<stack>.yaml` and read them through config. Select with `pulumi stack select`.
- **Config, not constants.** Provider settings (`gcp:project`, `gcp:region`) and app values
  live in `Pulumi.<stack>.yaml`. Secrets go in **encrypted** config
  (`pulumi config set --secret <key> <value>`) — never in code, `.env`, or plain YAML.
  Config *parsing* logic lives in `src/config.ts` as **pure functions** so it is unit-testable
  without the Pulumi runtime; `index.ts` reads `pulumi.Config` and passes plain values in.
- **ComponentResources for anything reused.** Wrap related resources in a
  `pulumi.ComponentResource` (see `src/components/gcs-bucket.ts`) with a namespaced type token
  (`wellforge:gcp:SecureBucket`), pass `{ parent: this }` to children, and call
  `registerOutputs`. Components encode secure defaults once (uniform bucket-level access,
  public-access prevention, versioning) so callers can't forget them.
- **Explicit resource names + labels.** Every resource takes a logical name; every GCP resource
  gets a consistent `labels` map (at least `environment` + `managed-by=pulumi`) built by
  `buildLabels()` — this is what the policy pack and cost tooling key off.
- **Outputs are `Output<T>`, not values.** Resource attributes resolve asynchronously. Compose
  with `.apply()` / `pulumi.interpolate` / `pulumi.all` — never `await` an Output or read
  `.value`. Export what other stacks or humans need via top-level `export const`.
- **Cross-stack wiring** uses `StackReference`, never hard-coded IDs.

## Policy-as-code (CrossGuard)

`policy/` is a self-contained policy pack enforcing guardrails at `preview`/`up` time:
buckets must enforce public-access prevention and uniform bucket-level access (`mandatory`),
and resources should carry an `environment` label (`advisory`). Run it locally with
`mise run infra:policy` (`pulumi preview --policy-pack ./policy`) and wire it into the deploy
workflow so no stack can be updated past the guardrails. The pack manages its own
dependencies and is intentionally outside the infra quality gate (guardrails are exercised at
deploy, not by unit tests).

## Testing

Unit tests use `pulumi.runtime.setMocks(...)` to intercept resource registration — they assert
the *inputs* your program produces (secure defaults, labels, naming) with **zero** cloud calls,
and run in CI on every PR. Set mocks **before** importing the module under test (dynamic
`import()` in the test). Pure helpers in `src/config.ts` are tested directly. `index.ts` is the
thin composition root and is intentionally not unit-tested (it is covered by `pulumi preview`).
Vitest coverage is measured over `src/**`.

## Deploying

- **No key files, ever.** Local: `gcloud auth application-default login` (ADC). CI: **Workload
  Identity Federation** — the GitHub Actions OIDC token is exchanged for short-lived GCP
  credentials; no `credentials.json` secret. `gcp-key*.json` / `credentials.json` are
  git-ignored as a backstop.
- **State backend.** Default is Pulumi Cloud (`pulumi login`). To self-host, use a GCS backend
  (`pulumi login gs://<state-bucket>`) — create that bucket out-of-band with versioning on.
- **Flow.** PR → `pulumi preview` (plan is the review artifact). Merge to `main` →
  `pulumi up` against the target stack, with `--policy-pack ./policy` enforced. This deploy
  workflow needs cloud credentials and is kept **separate** from `quality.yml` so PR CI stays
  keyless. Wire it during `/wellforge:new` stage 5 (connections) or with the devops agent.

## Spec-driven workflow

Feature work follows the WellForge spec-driven workflow. Artifacts live in `specs/`.
Drive it with the wellforge plugin commands:

- `/wellforge:spec` — capture the change (which stacks, blast radius, rollback)
- `/wellforge:plan` — turn the spec into a technical plan
- `/wellforge:tasks` — break the plan into actionable tasks
- `/wellforge:orchestrate` — execute the tasks

See `specs/README.md` for the short version.

